        // This b[i] is a multiple of n.
        // The segment is [1, n-1] (0-indexed: [0, n-2]). Length is n-1.
        // We need b[i] to be a multiple of (n-1).
        // This is the tricky part. The problem states "add a multiple of len".
        // The standard solution uses the property that for any x, there exists y such that x + y*n is a multiple of n-1.
        // No, this is not true.
        // The standard solution for this problem is to make all elements except the last one multiples of n.
        // Then make the last one zero. Then make all zero.

        // Strategy:
        // 1. For segment [1, n-1] (0-indexed: [0, n-2]):
        //    For each a[i], add b[i] such that (a[i] + b[i]) is a multiple of n.
        //    b[i] must be a multiple of (n-1).
        //    This is possible if we choose b[i] = (n-1) * k_i.
        //    We need a[i] + (n-1)*k_i = 0 (mod n).
        //    a[i] - k_i = 0 (mod n)  => k_i = a[i] (mod n).
        //    So, k_i = (a[i] % n + n) % n.
        //    Then b[i] = (n-1) * ((a[i] % n + n) % n).
        //    After this, a[i] becomes a[i] + b[i], which is a multiple of n.

        // Operation 1: Segment [1, n-1] (0-indexed: [0, n-2])
        std::cout << "1 " << n - 1 << "\n";
