    //   1. `elements[n-1].value + elements[n-2].value` (if elements[n-1] and elements[n-2] are in the same group)
    //   2. `elements[n-1].value + elements[n-2].value + h` (if elements[n-1] and elements[n-2] are in different groups)

    // The crucial observation is that the minimum possible value of `a_i + a_j` is `elements[0].value + elements[1].value`.
    // The maximum possible value of `a_i + a_j` is `elements[n-1].value + elements[n-2].value`.

    // Let `S_min = elements[0].value + elements[1].value`.
    // Let `S_max = elements[n-1].value + elements[n-2].value`.

    // If all elements are in one group:
    //   min_f = S_min
    //   max_f = S_max
    //   Goodness = S_max - S_min. This is `best_goodness` initially.

    // If elements are in two groups:
    //   There will be at least one pair (a_i, a_j) in different groups.
    //   So, values of type `X + Y + h` will appear.
    //   The smallest such value is `S_min + h`.
    //   The largest such value is `S_max + h`.

    //   The smallest value of `f` overall will be `min(S_min, S_min + h)`. This is `S_min`.
    //   This is achievable if `elements[0]` and `elements[1]` are in the same group.
    //   The largest value of `f` overall will be `max(S_max, S_max + h)`. This is `S_max + h`.
